bug.short_desc: [FastView] Fast view bar size depends on startup shell size

long_desc.thetext:
Build ID: I20071213-1700
Steps To Reproduce: 1. Start Eclipse with small window size and resize it 2. Dock several fast views, so that fast view bar size overgrows startup area 3. Only those fast view icons in startup area are shown. Changing fast view bar orientation reveals further problems
More information:
gtk 2.10.16

Can you provide a screen cap? Also, the current code -should- wrap the trim elements if there isn't enough space.
If you have so many views that there isn't enough space to show them all even though they're on their own line then this is an edge condition that isn't expected to take place under 'normal' conditions.
We're -considering- placing an arbitrary upper limit (10?) on the number of actual icons we show for a trim stack (using a chevron drop-down to show the rest). Note that if we go this route it'll use the limit regardless of how much actual screen space is available.

Does code cache initial shell size in some way ? Fast view bar adapts after resizing and restarting, but not after maximizing. It might have something to do with how window manager sets initial shell size (I use compiz-fusion, some swing apps have similar initial size and reparenting problems).
Probably related: changing fast view bar orientation does not work properly (see second screencap).
Created attachment 86386 Fast view bar is cropped
Created attachment 86387 Fast view bar after changing orientation

Bug manifests with kwin and compiz-fusion window managers in 3.4M4 when starting with maximized eclipse main window.
Seems to be fixed in 3.4M5.

Aleksander, I did some work in M5 to address a number of 'resize' issues around the Perspective Switcher and Fast View Bar...
I've just run through the scenarios you mention and don't see any issues (except the 'clipping' when the area is really too small to show everything but that's another issue).
I'm going to mark this as fixed...feel free to re-open should the issue re-appear...
